# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atole
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá is the only ritual food required in Candomblé; it is offered to all the orixás in the Candomblé pantheon.
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá made of white corn is offered to Oxala; that made of yellow corn is offered to Oxossi.
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá is made of white or red corn soaked in water for a day, which is then passed through a mill to make a paste or dough.
[src:atole/acaçá] The paste or dough is cooked in a pan and stirred continuously to reach a correct consistency.
[src:atole/acaçá] While warm, small portions of the dough are wrapped in a clean, folded clean banana leaf and passed over a fire.
[src:atole/acaçá] Finely ground white cornmeal can be substituted for soaked corn.
[src:atole/acaçá] The acaçá is cut into pieces of equal size.
[src:atole/acaçá] They are arranged on a platter to be placed on or near a *pegi*, or Candomblé altar.
[src:atole/acaçá] They also decorate other ritual foods in Candomblé, notably vatapá.
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto (Portuguese: *acaçá of black beans*) is a variation of the acaçá made from black beans, i.e., the black turtle bean (*Phaseolus vulgaris*).
[src:atole/acaçá] Black beans are substituted for soaked corn, similarly made into a paste, wrapped in banana leaves, and steamed in a pan.
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto is specifically offered to the god Ogum.
[src:atole/acaçá] The variation of acaçá is associated with Casa Fanti Ashanti, a Candomblé temple of the Jeje-Nagô tradition in the neighborhood of Cruzeiro do Anil, São Luís, in the state of Maranhão.
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá de leite (transl. acaçá of milk) is a fermented drink used in Candomblé rituals.
[src:atole/acaçá] It is made from a corn mush to which milk and other seasonings are added.
[src:atole/acaçá] Acaçá de leite is found in Candomblé temples in Bahia and the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:atole/acaçá] A variation, acaçá de leite de coco, is made from coconut milk.
[src:atole/acaçá] This variation is found in the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:atole/acequia] An **acequia** (Spanish: [aˈθekja]) or **séquia** (Catalan: [ˈsekiə, -a], also known as **síquia** [ˈsikiə, -a], all from Andalusian Arabic: (ال)ساقية, romanized: *(al-)sāqiya*) is a community-operated watercourse used in Spain and former Spanish colonies in the Americas for irrigation.
[src:atole/acequia] Acequias are found in parts of Spain and the Andes, northern Mexico, and what is now the Southwestern United States (New Mexico and Colorado).
[src:atole/acequia] In the United States, the oldest known irrigation canals are found throughout the historical region of Nuevo México and date back to 1200 BCE.
[src:atole/acequia] Irrigation was extensively used by the Pueblo peoples in Oasisamerica in the Pre-Columbian era.
[src:atole/acequia] In 1598, Hispanos of New Mexico arrived and brought irrigation methods from Europe.
[src:atole/acequia] This created a very distinctive indigenous and Hispanic tradition of irrigation and agriculture.
[src:atole/acequia] Acequias are filled by snow melt and rain to water orchards, gardens, and other agricultural fields.
[src:atole/acequia] Other than watering crops, acequias have deep cultural significance for many Indigenous and Native communities in New Mexico and Colorado.
[src:atole/acequia] The Spanish word *acequia* (and the Catalan word *séquia*) originate from Arabic word al-sāqiyah (الساقیة) which has more than one meaning: "the water conduit" or "one that bears water" as well as 'bartender' (from ‏سَقَى‎ *saqā*, "to give water, drink"), and also refers to a type of water wheel.
[src:atole/acequia] Traditionally, the Spanish acequias have been associated with the Muslim colonization of the Iberian Peninsula; however the most likely hypothesis is that they improved on irrigation systems that already existed since Roman times, or even before.
[src:atole/acequia] These ways of agricultural planning and colonization strategies come from the vast amount of cultural influences contributing to Spanish technology and governance.
[src:atole/acequia] Likely the most meaningful stemmed from the Muslims that ruled parts of Spain for as long as eight centuries.
[src:atole/acequia] Their ways of life influenced the Spanish and changed the way agriculture was done in Spain.
[src:atole/acequia] Acequias were later adopted by the Spanish and Portuguese (levadas on Madeira Island) and were utilized throughout their own colonies.
[src:atole/acequia] Similar structures already existed in places such as Mendoza and San Juan, Argentina where acequias today run along both sides of the city streets.
[src:atole/acequia] However, these acequias were originally dug by the Indigenous Huarpes long before the arrival of the Spanish.
[src:atole/acequia] The introduction of acequias by the Muslims allowed for more agricultural diversity, with crops such as sugar cane and citrus fruits introduced.
[src:atole/acequia] The system of the acequia has changed over time to avoid incidents of the resource from being overused or under-maintained.
[src:atole/acequia] The earliest known irrigation canals in the United States date back to 1200 BCE.
[src:atole/acequia] The Hohokam of Arizona built large irrigation canals beginning about 800 CE.
[src:atole/acequia] By the year 1400 CE, the Pueblo Indians in New Mexico were using canals and ditches to irrigate their crops.
[src:atole/acequia] With their arrival in New Mexico in 1598, the Spanish colonizers introduced their system of water management.
[src:atole/acequia] Subsequently, Spanish acequias were also built and used in California, Arizona, and Texas.
[src:atole/acequia] Acequias continue to provide a primary source of water for farming and ranching in the region of south central Colorado known as the Upper Rio Grande watershed or Rio Arriba and some 700 in northern New Mexico continue to function.
[src:atole/acequia] The governance of these acequias is the oldest style of European resource management still active in the United States today.
[src:atole/acequia] Acequias are gravity chutes, similar in concept to flumes.
[src:atole/acequia] Some acequias are conveyed through pipes or aqueducts, of modern fabrication or decades or centuries old (see transvasement).
[src:atole/acequia] For the system to function properly the channel must have a good gradient to maintain the flow of water.
[src:atole/acequia] When rainfall and snowmelt start to flow it is carried into the Acequia Madre and through the connecting channels throughout parts of New Mexico.
[src:atole/acequia] Known among water users simply as "the Acequia", various legal entities embody the community associations, or acequia associations, that govern members' water usage, depending on local precedents and traditions.
[src:atole/acequia] An acequia organization often must include commissioners and a majordomo who administers usage of water from a ditch, regulating which holders of water rights can release water to their fields on which days.
[src:atole/acequia] In New Mexico, by state statute, acequias as registered bodies must have three commissioners and a mayordomo.
[src:atole/acequia] Irrigation and conservation districts typically have their own version of mayordomos, usually referred to as "ditch riders" by members of the districts.
[src:atole/acequia] Acequias in New Mexico and Colorado have successfully developed and implemented changes in state water laws to accommodate the unique norms, customs, and practices of the acequia systems.
[src:atole/acequia] But the communal owners of the acequias in New Mexico experience strong economic pressure from land developers and inflation to sell the valuable acequia.
[src:atole/acequia] The customary law of the acequia is older than and at variance with the Doctrine of Prior Appropriation, and the statutes promulgating acequia water law represent a rare instance of water pluralism in Western water law in the United States (see Hicks & Peña (2003)).
[src:atole/acequia] For example, the Doctrine of Prior Appropriation is based on the principle of "first in use, first in right", while acequia norms incorporate not just priority but principles of equity and fairness.
[src:atole/acequia] This is evident in the fact that Prior Appropriation considers water to be a commodity owned by private individuals while acequia systems treat water as a community resource that irrigators have a shared right to use, manage, and protect.
[src:atole/acequia] The concept of a shared responsibility natural resources reflects the beliefs stemming from the Spanish and Indigenous people who brought the acequia to the U.S.
[src:atole/acequia] The plethora of cultural behaviors and values that created acequia communities still exist in the United States.
[src:atole/acequia] While Prior Appropriation doctrines allow for water to be sold away from the basin of origin, the acequia system prohibits the transfer of water from the watershed it is situated in, and thus considers water as an "asset-in-place".
[src:atole/acequia] The Prior regime is based on a governance regime in which the members of a mutual ditch company will vote based on their proportional ownership of shares, so that larger farmers have more votes.
[src:atole/acequia] In contrast, the acequia system follows a "one farmer, one vote" system that has led researchers to consider this a form of "water democracy".
[src:atole/acequia] Acequia law also requires that all persons with irrigation rights participate in the annual maintenance of the community ditch including the annual spring time ditch cleanup known as the *limpieza y saca de acequia*.
[src:atole/acequia] An example of the disputes over allocation of scarce water is the continuing controversy over acequias diverting water from Embudo Creek to the Mora River in New Mexico.
[src:atole/acequia] Settlers along the Mora River on the eastern side of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains constructed gravity-fed irrigation ditches (acequias) to divert water from three headwaters sources of the Rio Pueblo to the Mora River.
[src:atole/acequia] This diversion via acequias took 20 families three years to construct from 1879 to 1882.
[src:atole/acequia] The acequia was 8 mi (13 km) long and "constructed without the benefit of sophisticated tools and engineering know-how, accomplishing the seemingly impossible task" of bringing water from one side of the mountains to the other.
[src:atole/acequia] In drought years as much as one-half of the water of the Rio Pueblo is diverted to the Mora River.
[src:atole/acequia] In 2021, that water irrigated about 1,900 acres (770 ha) of agricultural land owned by 143 users.
[src:atole/acequia] The transfer of water was controversial.
[src:atole/acequia] The Picuris Pueblo contested the diversion of water from their territory to the Mora River as early as the 1860s and pursued a lawsuit against the diversions of water in the 1880s.
[src:atole/acequia] The suit was dismissed as no attorney would take the case.
[src:atole/acequia] Disputes about water continued into the 21st century.
[src:atole/acequia] In 2021, unidentified persons blocked the acequia directing water from Alamitos Creek with a mound of rocks and interrupted the flow of water to Mora Country.
[src:atole/acequia] The blockage was quickly removed, but the dispute over water rights continued.
[src:atole/adobada] "Carne adovada" is a baked meat dish that is a specialty in New Mexican cuisine.
[src:atole/adobada] The dish is cooked by baking at low heat wrapped completely in foil or in a covered dish like a casserole dish to keep the meat moist.
[src:atole/adobada] The southern New Mexican version is usually pork cut into strips and chunks.
[src:atole/adobada] Historically, before refrigeration, the pork was fermented in red chile in a crock using lactobacillus bacteria cultures.
[src:atole/adobada] Fermented meat was a way of preservation and imparted a "sour" taste to the pork which explains why some modern New Mexican adovada recipes call for a bit of white vinegar or lemon/lime juice.
[src:atole/adobada] The red chile is prepared "con pellejo" with bits of the chile skin using spices of fresh minced garlic and mortar and pestle ground oregano.
[src:atole/adobada] Comino (cumin), cilantro, and coriander seeds, that may or may not be toasted, are optional.
[src:atole/adobada] The dish is then baked until the meat is tender, moist and succulent on the inside while encrusted with a semidry and crisp red chile exterior that is almost blackened.
[src:atole/adobada] Other versions of red chile and boiled or braised pork may be claimed as carne adovada.
[src:atole/adobada] Other versions of red chile and pork-skin pellejo are actually what is known as chile Colorado.
[src:atole/adobada] Carne adovada may be served with a tortilla, beans and rice, fideos or homefries, or papas with a fresh vinegar slaw or salad.
[src:atole/adobada] Another version is found in central New Mexico.
[src:atole/adobada] Chunks of pork are dipped in milk and rolled in a dry rub of red chile con pellejo, garlic powder, salt, and cumin.
[src:atole/adobada] These are tossed into a large fry pot with chicharrones and deep fried until crisp on the outside and tender and succulent inside.
[src:atole/adobada] In certain states in Mexico, carne adobada refers to marinated pork meat.
[src:atole/adobada] It is a very common ingredient for tacos, in the area of Colima, Jalisco and Michoacán states.
[src:atole/adobada] In some parts of the state of Guerrero, it is known as "carne enchilada" which means chili dressed meat.
[src:atole/adobada] In the "Huasteca" area (San Luis Potosí, Tampico, Veracruz and Hidalgo) it may be called "cecina enchilada".
[src:atole/adobada] Most of the Mexican variations of adobada use guajillo or chipotle chiles for the marinade, both of which can be hot and spicy.
[src:atole/adobada] The combination of spices, chiles, and vinegar used for the marinade is called "adobo".
[src:atole/adobada] Numerous recipes and regional variations for the adobo seasoning impart different flavors to carne adobada.
[src:atole/adobada] Many carne adobada recipes from Mexico use the spices allspice, cinnamon, cloves, bay leaf, and/or nutmeg, which are not typically used in the New Mexico-style dish.
[src:atole/adobo] In the Philippines, the name *adobo* was given by colonial-era Spaniards on the islands to a different indigenous cooking method that also uses vinegar.
[src:atole/adobo] Although similar, this developed independently of Spanish influence.
[src:atole/adobo] In the years following the arrival of Europeans to the Americas, meat and fish began to be preserved by new methods.
[src:atole/adobo] Low temperatures facilitate food preservation, but in higher temperatures, other techniques, such as *adobo*, became necessary.
[src:atole/adobo] Animals were usually slaughtered in the coldest months of winter, but surplus meat had to be preserved in the warmer months.
[src:atole/adobo] This was facilitated through the use of *adobos* (marinades) along with paprika (a substance that may have antimicrobial properties due to the capsaicin content).
[src:atole/adobo] Paprika gives a reddish color to *adobos*, and the capsaicins in paprika dissolve in fats, allowing its penetration beyond the tissue surface.
[src:atole/adobo] The noun form of *adobo* describes a marinade or seasoning mix.
[src:atole/adobo] Recipes vary widely by region: Puerto Rican *adobo*, a rub used principally on meats, differs greatly from the Mexican variety.
[src:atole/adobo] Meat marinated or seasoned with an *adobo* is referred to as *adobado* or *adobada*.
[src:atole/adobo] In Mexico, *adobo* refers to a condiment or cooking sauce with a base containing chillies, particularly chipotle and ancho peppers.
[src:atole/adobo] An ancho pepper is a poblano chili that is dried after it turns red.
[src:atole/adobo] These sauces are used as a marinade and to add a smoky, spicy flavor.
[src:atole/adobo] Puerto Rican–style *adobo* is a seasoned salt that is generously sprinkled or rubbed on meats and seafood prior to grilling, sautéing, or frying.
[src:atole/adobo] There are two types of *adobo* on the island.
[src:atole/adobo] The wet rub, *adobo mojado*, consists of crushed garlic, olive oil, salt, turmeric, black pepper, false oregano, citrus juice and vinegar.
[src:atole/adobo] More widely used on the island is a dry mix, *adobo seco*.
[src:atole/adobo] It is easier to prepare and has a long shelf life.
[src:atole/adobo] *Adobo seco* consists of garlic powder, onion powder, turmeric, salt, black pepper, false oregano and sometimes dried citrus zest, avocado leaf and bay leaf.
[src:atole/adobo] Adobo is a typical dish of Peruvian cuisine, specifically in the area of Arequipa.
[src:atole/adobo] This is a dish of pork marinated in spices and vegetables, which are cooked in a clay pot until it becomes tender.
[src:atole/adobo] Bread is served alongside for dipping in the sauce.
[src:atole/adobo] In Filipino cuisine, *adobo* refers to a common and indigenous cooking method.
[src:atole/adobo] In the late 16th century, the Spanish referred to it as *adobo* due to its superficial similarity.
[src:atole/adobo] The main ingredients of Philippine *adobo* are native to Southeast Asia, namely vinegar, soy sauce or fish sauce, peppercorns, garlic, and bay leaves.
[src:atole/adobo] It does not traditionally use chilis, paprika, oregano, or tomatoes.
[src:atole/adobo] Rather, *adobo* is characteristically salty and sour, and often sweet taste.
[src:atole/adobo] Another version is cooking it with coconut milk which turns it into *ginataang adobo*.
[src:atole/adobo] In Uruguay, adobo is a spice mix of the same spices of the Spanish marinade.
[src:atole/adobo] Also, *adobar* is the act of using this mix as a condiment.
[src:atole/adobo] A sauce made of adobo, salt and water is called *mojo*.
[src:atole/adobo] One of the earliest references to adobo is found in the *Manual del Cocinero, Repostero, Pastelero, Confitero Y Botillero* by Mariano de Rementeria y Fica in 1850.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Because agave syrup dissolves quickly, it can be used as a sweetener for cold beverages.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] To produce agave syrup from the *Agave americana* and *A. tequilana* plants, the leaves are cut off the plant after it has been growing for seven to fourteen years.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] The juice is then extracted from the core of the agave, called the *piña*.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] The juice is filtered, then heated to break the complex components (the polysaccharides) into simple sugars.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] The main polysaccharide is called fructan, a polymer of fructose molecules.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] This filtered juice is then concentrated to a syrupy liquid, slightly thinner than honey.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Its color varies from light to dark amber, depending on the degree of processing.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] An alternative method used to process the agave juice without heat is described in a United States patent for a process that uses enzymes derived from the mold *Aspergillus niger* to convert the inulin-rich extract into fructose.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] In slightly greater detail, the polyfructose extract obtained from the mashed agave pulp is hydrolyzed via a chemical process patented in 1998, with inulin enzymes (obtained from *Aspergillus niger*), to produce a hydrolyzed fructose extract.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Concentrating the fructose yields the familiar syrup.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Agave syrup (nectar) is listed on the inventory of foods generally recognized as safe (GRAS) by the U.S.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] The carbohydrate composition in agave syrup depends on the species from which the syrup was made.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] In *A. tequilana* (blue agave), the syrup contains some 56% to 60% fructose, 20% glucose, and trace amounts of sucrose, whereas in *A. salmiana*, sucrose is the main sugar.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Fructose molecules in *A. tequilana* syrup chain together to create fructans and fructooligosaccharides, which have sweetening effects.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Blue-agave syrup is 1.4 to 1.6 times as sweet as sugar, and may be substituted for sugar in recipes.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Because it comes from a plant, it is widely utilized as an alternative to honey for those following a vegan lifestyle, and is often added to some breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] The specific strain known as blue agave syrup is not recommended for people with fructose intolerance.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Agave syrups are sold in light, amber, dark, and raw varieties.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Light agave syrup has a mild and almost neutral flavor, and is therefore sometimes used in delicate-tasting dishes and beverages.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Amber agave syrup has a medium-intensity caramel flavor, and is used in dishes and drinks with stronger flavors.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Dark agave syrup has even stronger caramel notes and imparts a distinct flavor to dishes, being used in some desserts, poultry, meat, and seafood dishes.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Both amber and dark agave syrups are sometimes used "straight out of the bottle" as a topping for pancakes, waffles, and French toast.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] The dark version is unfiltered and therefore contains a higher concentration of the agave plant's minerals.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] In a 100-gram reference amount, blue agave syrup supplies 1,297 kilojoules (310 kilocalories) of food energy and is a moderate source of vitamin C and several B vitamins (table).
[src:atole/agave-syrup] It is composed of 76% carbohydrates, 23% water, 0.4% fat, and negligible protein.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Having fructose as its primary sugar, blue agave syrup (56% fructose) is similar in fructose content to high-fructose corn syrup (55% fructose content), the most common sweetener used in US manufactured beverages.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] In a tablespoon amount (about 25 ml or 25 grams), blue agave syrup supplies 330 kJ (78 kcal), an amount similar to the value per tablespoon for high-fructose corn syrup (290 kJ or 70 kcal).
[src:atole/agave-syrup] Blue agave syrup has a relatively high sweetness factor because it is composed of 56% fructose, which is sweeter than sucrose.
[src:atole/agave-syrup] It has an effect on blood sugar comparable to fructose itself, as measured by its low glycemic index (GI) of between 11 and 19.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The plant is native to and domesticated in West Africa for its edible seeds and later for leaf and calyx production (for drinks and sauces).
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The drink made out of the flowers is known as *bissap* in Burkina Faso and Senegal, *zobo* in Nigeria or *sobolo* in Ghana.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] Although generally called a juice, which is sweetened and chilled, it is technically an infusion, and when served hot is called hibiscus tea.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In juice form, hibiscus or roselle juice is a dark, purple-red drink usually found cold in many West African countries.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] It tastes slightly like grape juice or cranberry juice, and can be served with mint leaves.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] It can also be served with any flavouring, such as with orange essence or ginger.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In Ghana, Nigeria, and Senegal, roselle juice is often served cold, while in Egypt and Sudan, it is often served warm.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The plant contains organic acids, polysaccharides, flavonoids and particularly anthocyanins, which provide the purple-red color.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The roselle hibiscus used to make the tea was domesticated in Africa, particularly the Western Sudan.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] West Africans have long cultivated and used roselle extensively.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] It is featured in numerous sauces, soups, and drinks.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In Africa, hibiscus tea is commonly sold in markets and the dried flowers can be found throughout West and East Africa.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] Many variations of the drink are consumed in West Africa and parts of Central Africa.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In American soul food cuisine, hibiscus tea is included in a category of "red drinks" associated with West Africa.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] However, Caribbean bissap and sorrel recipes, which were bought to North America by immigrants, have been largely adapted with other spices native to West Africa.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In Thailand, most commonly, roselle is prepared as a cold beverage, heavily sweetened and poured over ice, similar to sweetened fruit juices.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] Plastic bags filled with ice and sweetened *krachiap* can be found outside most schools and in local markets.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] It is sometimes combined with Chinese tea leaves, in the ratio of 4:1 by weight (1⁄5 Chinese tea).
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The beverage is also consumed in Malaysia, Cambodia, and Indonesia.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In Italy, hibiscus tea, known as *carcadè* or *karkadè* (from the Arabic word كَرْكَديه [karkaˈdiːh]), is usually consumed hot, often with the addition of sugar and lemon juice or orange slices.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] First introduced from Eritrea, it was widely used as a tea substitute when the country was hit by trade sanctions for its invasion of Abyssinia.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] In other European countries, it is used as an ingredient in mixed herbal tea (especially with malva flowers or rose hips in the mix, to enhance colouring).
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] Zobo is a local beverage in Nigeria made from dried hibiscus leaf and other ingredients.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The drink is commonly sold in restaurants and on roadsides.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] Zobo is made by boiling hibiscus leaves alongside ginger and cloves for less than an hour.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The solids are removed with a sieve, leaving behind the zobo juice.
[src:atole/agua-de-jamaica] The roselle drink has a flavour similar to cranberry juice and is ruby-red in colour.
[src:atole/aguachile] The origin of aguachile lies in the coast of Sinaloa, originally made with boiled water and chiltepin, a type of small round chili peppers from Sinaloa.
[src:atole/aguachile] This dish comes from the north west region of Mexico (mainly Sinaloa), and is normally prepared in a molcajete.
[src:atole/aguachile] Traditionally it is made of shrimp and raw fish fillet, submerged in liquid seasoned with chiltepin peppers, lime juice, salt, slices of cucumber and slices of red onion.
[src:atole/atole] Many Classic Maya painted vessels feature a genre of inscriptions known as the "dedicatory formula" or the "primary standard sequence" (PSS) and the two main ingredients mentioned in the contents section of the PSS were cacao and atole.
[src:atole/atole] In Mexico, the drink typically includes *masa* (corn hominy flour), water, *piloncillo* (unrefined cane sugar), cinnamon, vanilla, and optional chocolate or fruit.
[src:atole/atole] The mixture is blended and heated before serving.
[src:atole/atole] *Atole* is made by toasting *masa* on a *comal* (griddle), then adding water that was boiled with cinnamon sticks.
[src:atole/atole] In Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador, and Nicaragua, *atol de elote* (maize *atol*), or simply *atole*, is a common beverage.
[src:atole/atole] Pineapple *atol* (*atol de piña*) is also consumed in El Salvador.
[src:atole/atole] Guatemalan varieties include *atol shuco* ("dirty" *atol*, a reference to its darker color), consumed particularly often in the city.
[src:atole/atole] In Guatemala, the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development provided funding to INCAP to carry out a community randomized trial to test the hypothesis that improved protein intakes lead to better child development test scores.
[src:atole/atole] They were given a high-protein atole-like beverage made from INCAPARINA (a vegetable protein mixture developed by INCAP which mainly contains corn), dry skim milk, sugar, and a flavoring agent.
[src:atole/atole] In New Mexico, blue corn *atole* is finely ground cornmeal toasted for cooking, consumed as a grainy porridge-style drink served warm, usually sweetened with sugar or thinned with milk.
[src:atole/atole] It is usually served at breakfast like Cream of Wheat or oatmeal.
[src:atole/atole] Elders are said to have drunk *atole* because it gave them energy.
[src:atole/atole] A mother who is nursing will drink *atole* to give her more milk.
[src:atole/atole] The Puebloan peoples of New Mexico sometimes call *atole* *chaquehue* or *chaquewa*.
[src:atole/atole] The Ancestral Puebloans began to cultivate corn around 2000 BCE, and used advanced irrigation ditches as early as 205 CE.
[src:atole/atole] Later, during the time of Spanish colonialization, blue corn was irrigated by Moorish-influenced acequia systems.
[src:atole/atole] The Hopi plant blue corn seeds in bundles of several seeds to one hole, sometimes quite deep to reach ground water.
[src:atole/atole] Atole porridge is called mush by the Diné, and includes the addition of juniper ash.
[src:atole/atole] Atole flour is used to create Hopi piki bread.
[src:atole/atole] The beverage is referenced in the Spanish idiom *dar atole con el dedo* ("to give *atole* with the thumb"), which means to placate with deception.
[src:atole/atole] It may originate from the idea of wet nurses using *atole* on their thumbs to placate infants; alternatively, it may refer to the practice of distributing tamales and *atole* during periods of drought in pre-Columbian Mexico.
